PrefacePreface
'Go Green' a series of books on Environmental Education (EVS) is based on 
the EVS syllabus as prescribed by the N.C.E.R.T according to NEP and NCF.
To enable the students to realize their holistic potential in the process of 
learning, we have laid emphasis on the major skills that are to be 
developed through EVS. These skills include environmental sensitivity i.e. 
awareness, activity, projects, discussionsscientific skills
 and 
.
For the development of these skills the learners need to be aware of their 
surroundings and become keen observer. They should have the spirit of 
enquiry, be able to express their views and exhibit creativity and 
originality in doing activities and projects.
Keeping these needs of today's learners in mind we have prepared this 
series of EVS books.
These books will also enable the teachers to develop the skills in students 
as well as assess their learning process.
Any suggestions for the betterment of the book shall be thankfully 
acknowledged and incorporated in the subsequent editions.

How Do Families Change With Time?
Change is a rule of life. The families we see today are not like the ones we found in 
earlier times.
Many socio-economic forces are changing the family structure and quality of life in 
families today. People are adopting new ways of life and are constantly trying to 
adapt themselves to the changing environment. Let us understand this with an 
example of Arun's house.
The Changing FamiliesUnit–I : We And Our Family1
SMART TIPSSMART TIPSDuring earlier times, extended families often lived under one roof. They were 
known joint families. The traditional family system is rarely found nowadays. 
The joint families are being replaced by smaller nuclear families. Let us look at 
the reasons for this change.
(Knowledge)Environmental Studies-506

Why Do People Move?
People may have many reasons to move from one place to another. Some of them 
are–
! People living in villages move to cities or towns in search of better jobs.
! Improved life-style attracts people to bigger towns and cities.
! Sometimes people move to other countries for higher studies or better 
career prospects. This is called emigration. The people who migrate to 
another country and settle there are called immigrants for the new country.
! Natural calamities like earthquakes, floods, famines etc. force people to 
move to safer location.
! Some people have transferable jobs. They have to move to different places 
after a certain period of time. Their families also shift with them.
! Man-made calamities like terrorism and wars also force people to relocate.
! Adjustment problem in a joint family set up force people to migrate and live 
as nuclear families.
One day, Arun was sitting with his grand mother and going through the family 
album. He noticed the pictures of many relatives whom we had never met. He 
asked his grandmother about those relatives. His grandmother told him that many 
years ago, all of them lived together in a big house in Nainital. Many family 
members moved out of Nainital due to various reasons and their joint family 
splitted into a number of nuclear families.
Challenges of MigrationMoving to a new place leads to several problems.
! Adjustment to new surroundings and new people takes a lot of time.
! The children have to change their school, which gives rise to adjustment 
problem and affects their result.
! When the younger generation migrates, the elder generation becomes 
lonely.
! The members of the younger generation do not get love and care of their 
elders.
! The progress of any place is affected when the younger and talented people 
Environmental Studies-507

Changes in Values And BeliefsMigration not only changes the structure of a family but also affects the values and 
customs of a family. In earlier times , women were expected to stay at home and 
remain busy doing household work such as cooking, washing, cleaning, taking care 
of elders and children etc.
In modern times, women have become educated and entered almost all fields that 
were previously considered to be open only for men. Women are now doing well in 
engineering, law, politics, armed forces, sports, entertainment and so on.
With the changing time, many customs and traditions have changed. Like, it was 
seen in olden days that ladies covered their faces in front of their father-in-law. But 
today, fathers-in-law treat their daughters -in-law as their own daughters. 
Similarly, in earlier days all the important decisions were taken by the head of the 
family but now all important decisions are taken after the discussion and mutual 
consent of family members.
Today, women are managing the work outside the home too. So, men take an 
active part in various household activities to reduce the load of work at women. 
Children also help their parents in managing the house.
It was seen earlier that the son of a farmer became a farmer, the son of a tailor 
became a tailor but now this has changed. Now, the son of a farmer becomes an IAS 
officer or more. Now, people have become aware and do the work with their own 
will and interest.
Some values however remain unchanged. The younger members respect the 
elders. Elders also love and take care of the youngers.
Advantages of MigrationMigration has many positive effects also.
! It leads to better job and educational opportunities.
! It usually results in improvement of life style.
! It leads to cooperation and mixing of cultures.
In Mauritius , about 70% population are of Indian origin.

! In winters, when your fingers get numb due to severe cold, you put them 
against your mouth and blow hard. Why?
! When you want to go to play after finishing the milk and the milk is too hot, 
you blow on it. Why?
! Do you notice something strange in the above two cases?
Blowing air over glass of hot milkBlowing air over hands in winterBreathing in,
Breathing Out2
Breathing OrgansMany organs are involved in the process of breathing. Out of them, lungs are the 
primary organs. 
Your breath can both warm and cool an object. Whether the breath will cool 
or warm something depends on which of the two is hotter–the object or your 
breath. In cold weather, your breath is obviously warmer than your hands. 
But, compared to hot milk your breath is cooler.
We breathe all the time– while talking, walking, eating, sleeping etc. We 
breathe in oxygen and breathe out carbon dioxide.
Let's KnowLet's KnowUnit–I : We And Our FamilyEnvironmental Studies-512

Process of BreathingBreathing is the process that helps our body to absorb oxygen and remove carbon 
dioxide from it. It involves two main processes. They are—
Nose— We take in air through our nose. The two nostrils in our nose contain a 
sticky mucous and tiny hair which clean this air by 
trapping the dust particles.
Trachea— It is also called wind pipe. It is a long tube 
that carries air into the lungs through a pair of thin 
tubes called bronchi.
Bronchi— These are two tubes that help air reach the 
pair of lungs.
Lungs— These are a pair of spongy bag-like organs 
located on either side of the breast bone in the chest 
cavity. Our right lung is bigger than our left lung.
Diaphragm— It is a strong muscle located just below the lungs. It helps to move the 
lungs up and down.
1. Inhalation (Breathing in)— When we breathe 
in, oxygen rich air enters our nose and goes to 
our lungs through the windpipe and bronchi. 
This process is called inhalation. While 
inhaling, the diaphragm contracts to make 
more space for lungs. The lungs then enlarge 
to take in more air.
Inhalation(Breathing in)Deep breathing is one of the best way to lower stress in the body. 
This is because when we breathe deeply, it sends a message to our 
brain to calm down and relax.
You 
 KnowMust 
(Knowledge)Environmental Studies-513

2. Exhalation (Breathing out)— After a short 
span of time of inhaling, we breathe carbon 
dioxide out of our lungs. This process is called 
exhalation. When we breathe out, the 
diaphragm relaxes and moves up and the 
carbon dioxide is pushed out of the lungs 
which is finally pushed out through the nose 
or mouth.
Breathing RateWe do not breathe at a constant rate. Breathing rate keeps changing from time to 
time. When we run very fast or after a vigrous exercise, we breathe heavily and the 
breathing rate increases. Do you know why?
This is because when we exercise or run fast, the demand for oxygen to be brought 
into the body becomes higher, and the need for carbon dioxide to be given out is 
equally high. The heart then starts pumping faster to circulate the oxygen through 
the body quicker and to get rid of carbon dioxide.
Exhalation(Breathing out)My Breath— Hot/Cold and HumidSending a stream of air with force from mouth is called blowing. It is simply 
exhaling air. We use our breath to make hot things cold and cold things hot. Let's 
see some examples of our daily life.
! In winters, we blow on our palms to make 
them warm. This is because our body 
Otemperature is 37 C which is much higher 
than the temperature outside. Thus, the 
air exhaled by our mouth is warm and 
makes our palms warm.
Blowing on palmsEnvironmental Studies-514

Chest Expansion During BreathingAs we breathe in, the diaphragm contracts, the ribs and the chest cavity expand 
allowing air to fill up the lungs. When we breathe out, the diaphragm relaxes and 
the chest cavity goes back to its normal size.
Protecting LungsAlthough tiny hair and mucous in our nostrils trap most of the dirt, sometimes 
minute particles of dust and smoke do manage to reach our lungs and cause severe 
illness. Inhaling poisonous gases from vehicles and factories too can cause many 
breathing problems. Diseases like asthma and bronchitis are increasing rapidly due 
to increasing level of harmful gases in the air.
Though we can protect our lungs from the 
poisonous gases and dust particles by wearing 
masks, it is not a solution. The real solution lies 
in working towards decreasing air pollution. 
Some ways by which the level of air pollution 
can be decreased are—
! Reduce the number of trips you take in 
your car.
! We blow on a glass of hot milk to make it cold. 
The air from our mouth which is 
comparatively cooler than the air around the 
glass, takes place of the hot air and lowers 
down the temperature of the milk.
! During winters it is a common observation 
that the glass surfaces or mirrors become 
cloudy when we blow on them. This is 
because our breath contains water vapour. 
After touching the cold surface, the water 
vapour condenses making it cloudy. The air 
containing water vapour is called humid air. 
Thus, our breath is humid.
Blowing on window paneBlowing on hot milkEnvironmental Studies-515

! Avoid burning leaves, trash and other materials.
! Plant more and more trees.
! Instead of diesel and petrol, use fuels like LPG and CNG which do not cause 
pollution.
! Install pollution control devices in the factories.

Wellness :
Health and Hygiene3
HealthHealth is defined as the state of complete physical and mental well-being of a 
person. This means that both the body and the mind must be completely fit for a 
person to be healthy.
To be healthy we must–
! take balanced diet
! exercise regularly
! have proper rest
! maintain good hygiene
! protect ourselves from diseases
! maintain good postureGood health, as we all know, is very important. But do you know what we 
actually mean by 'health'?
Let's KnowLet's KnowUnit–I : We And Our FamilyEnvironmental Studies-520

Balanced diet– We need food to live. Our food should have 
enough nutrients so that we grow and stay healthy. The 
main nutrients include carbohydrates, fats, proteins, 
vitamins and minerals. In addition, our body also needs 
roughage and plenty of water. It is important to eat the right 
kind of food in the right quantity. Eating too little or too 
much food can make us unhealthy. 
A diet that provides us all the nutrients in the right quantity to remain healthy and 
disease free is called a balanced diet.
Deficiency of nutrients in our food can lead to various diseases.
Prevention is always better than cure.
You 
 KnowMust 
(Knowledge)DiseasesDisease is defined as the condition in which our body does not function properly. 
Diseases can occur due to many reasons. They may occur due to deficiency of 
nutrients in the diet, eating contaminated food or drinking contaminated water 
etc.
Diseases can be divided into two categories–
! Communicable diseases
! Non-communicable diseases
 
Diseases which spread from one person to 
Communicable diseases– 
another are called communicable diseases. These diseases are caused by 
germs or microbes. They can spread through contaminated food, water, air, 
insect bites or direct or indirect contact with an infected person.
 
Examples of communicable diseases are–
 
common cold, typhoid, dengue, malaria, measles, cholera, Covid-19, 
tuberculosis etc.
 
The best method to prevent communicable diseases is to 
Prevention– 
maintain proper hygiene of body, food, water and surroundings.
 
Some other methods are–
! Educating the people about the causes of such diseases.
! Proper vaccination, particularly during an epidemic.
